   >>>[David Sternlight writes:]
 >>>This is an argument with blinders on. Consider how many lives could have
 >>>been saved at Pearl Harbor if the traffic from Japan had been decrypted
 >>>more rapidly. Consider the terrorist plots thwarted. Consider the insights
 >>>into, say, Saddam's war plans.

   >>[Rob Ryan writes:]
 >>Right.  All we had to do was convince the Japanese (before Pearl Harbor)
 >>that they were only supposed to use crypto for which the keys were managed
 >>by U.S.  escrow agencies.  "But we promise not to peek ... really."
 >>
 >>And sure, terrorists are definitely going to use crypto that the gov't has
 >>the keys to decrypt.  Only stupid terrorists that is.

   >[David Sternlight writes:]
 > This is a good example of why newsgroup discussions are so frustrating, and
 >go on interminably. My comment was designed to do only one thing--to refute
 >an obviously false statement. Rather than either accept the refutation or
 >show how the comment didn't refute the statement, it's used by the above
 >writer to start a wholly different point, but in a tone that implies my
 >comment, for the purpose it was posted, was refuted.

  Ryan's comments refute Sternlight's original comments by demonstrating
that the means in question (crypto controls, key escrow) do not in fact
acheive the benefits cited by Sternlight (protection against enemies and
terrorists).

